body:
This PR is a first effort for the long-term goal to add an [HPy](https://github.com/hpyproject/hpy) backend to Cython. The main objective here is to get some feedback on how to structure the code and what else needs to be considered. So, this is an explicit request for comments.

The main idea is to move C code generation into the `CCodeWriter`. For that, I've introduced a new class `HPyCodeWriter` that inherits from `CCodeWriter` and the new writer emits HPy API calls/code instead of CPython API calls/code. Then, we can use two different writers to run the same generation step.

As we have already discussed in a meeting on September 3rd, 2021 with @scoder, Cython now emits C API and HPy API code and the different sections are protected by ifdefs like this:
```
# ifndef HPY
  /* C API code */
#endif

#ifdef HPY
  /* HPy API code */
#endif
```
This is realized by introducing code sections for HPy (see `Code.py: code_layout`).
Some of the sections are independent of the API and can be shared (e.g. `string_decls` which defines global `const char *` variables).

A lot of work still needs to be done (of course) but the first simple example `hpy_basic.py` is already working (C only).

comment_data.body: I think there should probably be a separate `CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_HPY` section for this. Or would you consider it orthogonal to a specific ~runtime~ compile time environment?
Interesting. Could you add a comment here on what makes this special?
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -2253,6 +2344,14 @@ class CPySSizeTType(CIntType):
     def sign_and_name(self):
         return "Py_ssize_t"
 
+class CHPySSizeTType(CIntType):

@@ -111,7 +111,7 @@ def __repr__(self):
 #: from their Python 2 names to their Python 3 names by Cython
 #: when building in Python 3.x,
 #: so that they do not get in the way even if this option is enabled.
-cache_builtins = True
+cache_builtins = False

comment_data.body:
For now, yes, I think we should have a separate `CYTHON_COMPILING_IN_HPY` section.
I'm just not sure if we will need it in a long term.
The reason for this block is that HPy does currently not support multi-phase init (and disabling it saved me a lot of work) and the Refnanny is probably not required for HPy at all since HPy comes with a debug mode. Or do you think that the Refnanny would also make sense for HPy?
Sorry, please just ignore that. I won't, ofc, ever merge this change. I just need to migrate the cache logic.
comment_data.diff_hunk:
@@ -111,7 +111,7 @@ def __repr__(self):
 #: from their Python 2 names to their Python 3 names by Cython
 #: when building in Python 3.x,
 #: so that they do not get in the way even if this option is enabled.
-cache_builtins = True
+cache_builtins = False

comment_data.body:
HPy defines its own size type, i.e. `HPy_ssize_t`, similar to `Py_ssize_t`. This is mainly done to avoid importing `Python.h` in HPy which would then mean that any HPy extension transitively depends on Python's C API.
I would say, there is nothing special about this type. I introduced it because it has a different name and because the conversion functions are also named differently.
